ut 1501","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England":"Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gobbett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: nickname, perhaps from Middle English (Old French)  <i>gobet</i> ‘lump, morsel’ or from Middle English  <i>go bet</i> ‘go better’; compare Walter Gobiforn (‘go before’), 1212 in   Pleas   (Yorks); John Gobisid’ (‘go beside’), 1379 in   Yorks Poll Tax  , and   Golightly  .","2  English: variant of   Godbold  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gobat","meanings":["1  English:  see  Godbold  .","2  English:  see  Gobbett  ."]},{"name":"Yorks Poll Tax","meanings":["1  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name   May   + the patronymic marker  <i>-son</i>.","2  English: a northern spelling of   Mason  . Compare Adam de Morton,  <i>mayson</i>, 1371 in   Yorks Poll Tax  ."]},{"name":"Pleas","meanings":["English: variant of   Place   1 or 2."]},{"name":"Godbold","meanings":["English (Suffolk): from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Godebald</i>, <i>Godbaud</i>, a medieval French form of the ancient Germanic name <i>Godebald</i>, composed of the elements <i>gōd</i> ‘good’ or <i>god</i> ‘god’ + <i>bald</i> ‘bold, brave’."]},{"name":"Gobet","meanings":["English:  see  Gobbett  ."]},{"name":"Golightly","meanings":["English (Durham): nickname, perhaps for a messenger, from Middle English <i>gō(n)</i> ‘to go’ (Old English <i>gān</i>) + <i>lihtly</i> ‘lightly, swiftly’ (Old English <i>lēoht(līc)</i>).","Scottish and English: altered form of Scottish <b>Galletly</b>, a variant of Irish <b>Mac an Ghallóglaigh</b>, see   Gallogly  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":48,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":57,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":68,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Gobbett was born about 1501, in Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1501–":"umbes 1501–Surnud","1519–1586":"1519–1586","1501–Male":"1501–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1586":"1586","about 1501":"umbes 1501","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England":"Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1501–":"noin 1501–Kuollut","1519–1586":"1519–1586","1501–Male":"1501–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1586":"1586","about 1501":"noin 1501","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England":"Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"about 1501–":"environ 1501–Décédé","1519–1586":"1519–1586","1501–Male":"1501–Décédé","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1586":"1586","about 1501":"environ 1501","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England":"Dickleburgh, Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Gobbett est né environ 1501, à Dickleburgh, Norfolk, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"about 1501–":"um 1501–Verstorben","1519–1586":"1519–1586","1501–Male":"1501–Verstorben","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1586":"1586","about 1501":"um 1501","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England":"Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England","lifeSummary":"Robert Gobbett wurde um 1501 in Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"about 1501–":"about 1501–Desede","1519–1586":"1519–1586","1501–Male":"1501–Desede","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1586":"1586","about 1501":"about 1501","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England":"Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England"},"hu":{"about 1501–":"1501 körül–elhunyt","1519–1586":"1519–1586","1501–Male":"1501–elhunyt","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1586":"1586","about 1501":"1501 körül","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England":"Dickleburgh, Norfolk, England"},"id":{"about 1501–":"sekitar 1501–Telah Meninggal","1519–1586":"1519–1586","1501–Male":"1501–Telah Me